The PackBuffer and UnPackBuffer classes provide a convenient mechanism
for packing and unpacking buffers for communication.  They are
currently implemented for use with MPI, with which they use MPI's Pack
and UnPack routines.
 
 
The PackBuffer class dynamically resizes its internal buffer to contain
enough memory to pack the entire object.  When deleted, this internal buffer
is deleted.
 
const char* buf()
 
  This method returns a pointer to the internal buffer.
 
int len()
 
  This method returns the amount of memory used to pack the data.
 
void reset()
 
  This method resets the pointer used for packing, which effectively resets
  the PackBuffer class to pack new data.
 
void pack(const <type>* data, const int num=1)
void pack(const <type>& data)
 
  The pack methods are defined for a variety of standard data types.
  The first pack method can be used to pack a vector of <type>'s, and the
  second pack method can be used to pack a single <type>.
 
PackBuffer& operator<< (PackBuffer& buff, const <type>& data)
 
  The in-stream operator provides a convenient shorthand for the second
  pack method.
 
 

The BasicArray defines a basic array data type that manages the
allocation and deallocation of memory.  This code is strongly
influenced on the discussion of reference counting in C. S. Horstmann,
"Mastering C++ - An introduction to C++ and object-oriented programming
for C and Pascal programmers."  This code represents an extension of
the vector class developed by Brian Bartell, UC San Diego.



The ArrayData class maintains the following data:

  Data		a pointer to data
  ref		a reference counter for this class instance
  Len		the length of the array
  own		the ownership flag

The ownership categories for the data are:

  DataNotOwned     - Data owned by some other SimpleArray
  AcquireOwnership - Data originally copied from another SimpleArray
  AssumeOwnership  - Data pointer points to another SimpleArray's data



A BasicArray uses the ArrayData class to maintain a reference counter.  This array
class preserves the copy semantics of the = operator.  The &= operator can be
used to explicitly share data between two BasicArray classes.  

int len() const

  This method returns the length of the array (number of objects, not bytes)

T* data() const

  The method returns a pointer to the array.

BasicArray();

  The empty constructor;

BasicArray(const int len, T *d=NULL, const EnumDataOwned o);

  A constructor that sets up the class with given data.

BasicArray(const BasicArray& array);

  The copy constructor.


int resize(const int);

  The resize method copies the existing data into the array.

BasicArray<T>& operator=(const BasicArray<T>& array);	// construct and copy

  The equals operator constructs a new array and copies 'array' into it.

BasicArray<T>& operator&=(const BasicArray<T>& array);	// copy ptr

  The equals& operator copies the pointer to ArrayData into the class and
  updates the ArrayData's reference counter.

BasicArray<T>& operator<<(const BasicArray<T>& array);	// copy array

  The << operator copies the data from 'array' onto the existing array in 
  this class.

BasicArray<T>& operator=(const T& val);

  Sets all of the elements in the array equal to 'val'.

T & operator[](const int ndx);

  Returns a reference to the 'ndx'th element of the array.

const T & operator[](const int ) const;

  Returns a const reference to the 'ndx'th element of the array.

BasicArray<T>& set_data(const int len, T *data, const EnumDataOwned o);

  Sets the data in the ArrayData object equal to 'data'.  If the ArrayData
  object contained a non-null pointer to an array, and it was owned, then
  that data is deleted.  Otherwise it is discarded and ignored.

BasicArray<T>& set_data(const BasicArray<T>& vec, const int start, const int newlen);

  Sets the data in the ArrayData object equal to some subset of the
  data in 'vec'.  If the ArrayData object contained a non-null pointer
  to an array, and it was owned, then that data is deleted.  Otherwise
  it is discarded and ignored.  The 'start' value determines where in
  vec's array the ArrayData points to.  The 'newlen' value indicates
  the length of the array pointed by ArrayData (the default is -1,
  which indicates the rest of the arrray).

BasicArray<T>& set_subvec(const int start, const int len,
                                 const BasicArray<T>& datavec, const int offset);

  Copies data from datavec[offset-start]...datavec[offset+len-start-1] into 
  the ArrayData at [start]...[start+len-].

BasicArray<T>& at(const int start, const int newlen, BasicArray<T>* vec) const;

  If vec is not supplied, this method constructs a new BasicArray.  And calls
  set_subvec.  Otherwise, it simply calls set_subvec.
